cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Well done, Roberta. The play was straight forward. However, let me just do a quick review of Bergen Raises for those not familiar with them. In SAYC with no Bergen Raises, if you have a limit raise, you would bid 3H with my hand. That would show 10-12 points and four hearts if you are not playing Bergen Raises. However, Marty Bergen feels that based on the law of total tricks, with a nine card fit, you want to preempt the opponents by bidding 3H with a weak hand--less than 7 points. So, he decided 3H would show a weak hand with four card support. |
PG| ***** 144 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|That makes it more difficult for the opponents to bid when they have a lot of points. The question then is, how do you show a limit raise. Well Bergen decided there are four types of hands with four card support. The strong raise, 13+ with four card support, is taken care of by bidding Jacoby 2N. There is also the limit raise 10-12, the constructive raise 7-9, and  the weak raise less than 7. So, 1H-P-3H is the weak raise (< 7). There are two bids available to show the constructive raise and limit raise. |
PG| ***** 145 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|They are 3C and 3D. As originally defined by Bergen, 3C shows the constructive raise, and 3D shows the limit raise. However, many people felt that it would be more advantageous to be able to explore for game with a limit raise than a constructive raise. So, they play Reverse Bergen, which simply reverses the meaning of 3C and 3D. 3C is a limit raise, 3D is a constructive raise. That is the way I play it. However, Marty Bergen feels that it is more important to be able to explore with a constructive raise.|
